'''Education in El Salvador''' follows a (1 or 2) 9-2-5 [[educational system]], which is regulated by the country's Ministry of Education:<ref>"[http://www.mined.gob.sv/ Ministry of Education. Government of El Salvador]" </ref>
== Education levels == *One or two years of ''[[Preschool|Preschool Education]]'' (called ''kinder'', short for [[kindergarten]]), which is not part of the State's educational system. *Nine years of ''[[Primary education|Basic Education]]'' divided in three ''cycles'' of three grades each: **1st Cycle: from 1st to 3rd grades **2nd Cycle: from 4th to 6th grades **3rd Cycle: from 7th to 9th grades; which is a transition to [[secondary education]] (e.g. specialized teachers for each assignment). *Two (or an optional three years technical program) of ''[[High school|Middle Education]]'', called ''[[bachillerato]]'': **Two year ''General Bachelor's Degree'' **Three year ''Technical Bachelor's Degree'' (''e.g. Accounting, Secretariat, Electronics and Computer Science, etc.'') *Five years (minimum) of ''[[Higher education|Higher Education]]'', consisting of [[University|university education]] or other [[tertiary education]].
== Dynamics == The national educational system is not the only one available. Pre-university education is not free. The State provides [[public education]] for which a fee is paid if the person paying can afford it and only one payment per family is made (i.e. siblings pay only one fee). Public education is inconsistent in quality, being extremely poor in rural areas and dubiously efficient in urban areas, becoming one of the State's greatest challenges.
In 1992 the Minister of Education Cecilia Gallardo de Cano embarked on a reform program of basic education. In 2010 the literacy rate was 82% for both sexes.
== Higher education == {{See|List of universities in El Salvador}}
The [[University of El Salvador]] (UES) is the largest (and only) public university in the country. However, classes are constantly stopped for protests. The University of El Salvador has one main campus in San Salvador and three more campuses in Santa Ana, San Miguel and San Vicente.
There are also [[List of universities in El Salvador|many private universities]] as alternatives to UES.
In Dec. 2014, the government of El Salvador entered into partnership with the United States Agency for International Development, in hopes of improving institutions of higher learning within the country with updated curricula and faculty training.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/1635105111/fulltext/BF3036B112534654PQ/1?accountid=15131|title=New Higher Education Project Launches in El Salvador, Aims to Boost Economic Growth|last=|first=|date=December 11, 2014|website=ProQuest|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
