'''Legalswipe''' is a free [[mobile app|app]] that offers general [[legal advice]] and protection to people randomly stopped and questioned by police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/06/29/new-smartphone-app-offers_n_7690380.html |publisher=[[Huffington Post Canada]] |title= Legalswipe, New App, Offers Legal Advice For Random Cop Encounters |date= June 26, 2015}}</ref> Christien Levien, a [[Law of Canada|Canadian lawyer]], conceived Legalswipe to educate civilians about their [[Natural and legal rights|legal rights]] during their interaction with police. The idea of the app was born from Levien's encounter with police and his difficulty in navigating the legal system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/ontariotoday/2015/08/25/is-carding-inherently-racist |publisher=[[CBC.ca]] |title= Is carding inherently racist? |date= August 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/sci-tech/smartphone-app-offers-legal-advice-for-police-encounters-1.2446034 |publisher=CTV News |title= Smartphone app offers legal advice for police encounters |date= June 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lawtimesnews.com/201602155222/focus-on/focus-apps-can-unchain-lawyers-from-desk-developer |publisher=Law Times News |title= Focus: Apps can unchain lawyers from desk: developer |date= February 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://commonlaw.uottawa.ca/en/news/alumnus-christien-levien-14-creates-legal-advice-app-legalswipe |publisher= University of Ottava |title= Alumnus Christien Levien (’14) Creates Legal Advice App, Legalswipe |date= July 22, 2015}}</ref>
==Features== The free app, available for Apple and Android devices, informs its users about their rights and provides several key features through a series of simple contextual menus and cues:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cp24.com/lifestyle/technology/new-app-offers-legal-advice-for-random-police-encounters-1.2446020 |publisher=[[CP24]] |title= New app offers legal advice for random police encounters |date= June 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2082234/new-smartphone-app-offers-legal-advice-for-random-police-encounters |publisher= [[Global News]] |title= New smartphone app offers legal advice for random police encounters |date= June 29, 2015}}</ref> * A user-friendly navigation system (interface) provides contextual, situation-based cues to provide information related to a situation. * A personalized message of updates about [[Geographic coordinate system|geographic location]] is sent to [[In Case of Emergency|emergency contacts]]. * Exact words to use and applicable rights are provided. * Audio, photo, and video recordings are saved and uploaded to [[Dropbox (service)|Dropbox]], Google Drive, OneDrive, or Box.
When [[user interface design|user feedback]] indicated that the navigation was challenging, the app was redesigned by a group of [[Humber College]] students in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://humber.ca/today/news/humber-students-redesign-legalswipe-app |publisher=Humber |title= Humber Students Redesign Legalswipe App |date= July 27, 2017}}</ref>
==Reception== Legalswipe has been favorably received and the object of a lot of attention from Canada and the United States.<ref name="torontostar">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2015/07/02/lawyer-in-your-pocket-app-helps-during-police-carding.html |publisher= [[Toronto Star]] |title= Lawyer-in-your-pocket app helps during police carding |date= July 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2015/07/03/legalswipe-lawyer-in-your-pocket-app-helps-during-police-carding.html |publisher= [[StarMetro (newspaper)|Metro]] |title= Legalswipe: Lawyer-in-your-pocket app helps during police carding |author= A. Joseph |date= July 3, 2015}}</ref> Legalswipe was launched in June 2015 and has been downloaded over 15,000 times in its first two months.<ref name="milestone"/> The app has been endorsed by former [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen’s Park]] speaker [[Alvin Curling]] and journalist [[Desmond Cole]].<ref name="torontostar"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecaribbeancamera.com/news/stories/carding-weve-got-an-app-for-that/ |publisher= The Caribbean Camera |title= Carding? We’ve got an app for that |date= July 9, 2015}}</ref>
